The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, April 5: Infrastructure projects in south Indian cities have attracted 70 per cent of the private sector investment in the last four years because of better state policies and faster rise in per capita income, an Assocham study said. Southern cities like Hyderabad, Bangalore and Chennai have accounted for 70 per cent of the total private investment in infrastructure projects (out of) the six metro cities in India. Calcutta, Mumbai and Delhi accounted for the remaining 30 per cent, Assocham president Sajjan Jindal said.                            
	 New Delhi, April 5: The government is working on ways to reduce the burden of levy on the packaged software segment to save them from double taxation. We are discussing on the modalities of their taxation. Right now there is no definite way of treating packaged software as goods or services. We are finding out a way to tax them in a manner so that they are not doubly taxed, said a finance ministry official.                            
	 New Delhi, April 5: The State Bank of India has given a return of 9.7 per cent on provident fund deposits, which is over half a percentage more than the best among private sector asset managers during the quarter ended December 2008.                            
	 Dubai, April 5: The Gulf Cooperation Council economies are expected to slip into a recession in 2009 as a result of the severe deterioration in the global economic scene, a National Bank of Kuwait report has said.                            
	 Mumbai, April 5: The Bank of Baroda expects its loan growth in 2009-10 to decline to 20 per cent, because of economic downturn, bank chairman and managing director, M.D. Mallya said.                             
	 Mumbai, April 5: The credit crisis has impacted fund raising by Indian companies during the first 10 months of the last financial year, a Ficci-Ernst amp; Young report has said.                            
	 Mumbai, April 5: Leading BPO firm Firstsource Solutions has completed a restructuring exercise creating four verticals with separate chiefs, designed to facilitate better customer focus, develop domain expertise and optimise efficiencies.                                                                                                                           
